%N A397644 a(n) is the number of subsequences divisible by 3 taken from the n-th number whose digits are in nondecreasing order and all digits <= 3.
%C A397644 a(n) is the number of subsequences divisible by 3 of A397643(n).
%C A397644 Divisibility mod 3 of a subsequence only depends on digits mod 3. Duplicate subsequences are included.
%C A397644 Empirically, a(n) approaches 1/3 the number of nonempty subsequences: (2^A055642(A397643(n))-1)/3. - _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 04 2026
%H A397644 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A397644/b397644.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A397644 The 11-th number with digits in nondecreasing order and all digits <= 3 is 112. There are two subsequences of 112 that are divisible by 3: 12 and 12.
%o A397644 (PARI) first(n) = {my(res = List()); for(i = 1, oo, forvec(x = vector(i, j, [1, 3]), listput(res, mod3(fromdigits(x))[1]); if(#res >= n, return(res)), 1))}
%o A397644 mod3(n) = {my(d = digits(n), v = [1,0,0], i, j, cv); forstep(i = #d, 1, -1, cv = v; for(j = 1, #v, cv[(j + d[i])%3 + 1] += v[j%3 + 1]); v = cv); v[1]--; v}
%Y A397644 Cf. A055642, A372600, A397643.
%K A397644 nonn,base,new
%O A397644 1,9
%A A397644 _David A. Corneth_, Jul 03 2026
